owers, large woody pods", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Precocious, heavy cropping in subtropical areas", "growing_notes": "EXCELLENT FOR humid subtropical climates SUBTROPICAL. Species: Pachira insignis/glabra (NOT true chestnut - Malvaceae family). Tolerates frost inland from Bundaberg. Grown successfully in humid subtropical climates area. Frost-free location preferred. Full sun to partial shade. Well-drained soil. Requires frequent watering. Not a true chestnut but produces edible nuts after proper preparation.", "availability": "Daley''s Fruit Tree Nursery, tropical plant nurseries"}, {"name": "WATER CHESTNUTS - TRADITIONAL INDIAN CULTIVATION", "slug": "water-chestnuts-traditional-indian-cultivation", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 0, "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Singhara / Singara (Water Chestnut) 🏆", "slug": "singhara-singara-water-chestnut", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 1, "origin": "Indigenous to India - traditional crop in Bihar, West Bengal, Jharkhand, tropical monsoon climates backwaters", "traits": "Aquatic floating plant, grows in ponds/wetlands, black/green horned nuts with 2-4 spines", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "4-12 tonnes/hectare. Bihar Large Red: 7 t/ha. Green Spineless: up to 12 t/ha", "growing_notes": "Species: Trapa natans (Lythraceae - aquatic annual, NOT a tree). EXCELLENT FOR tropical monsoon climates WETLANDS/BACKWATERS. Indigenous traditional Indian crop. Grows in tropical/subtropical freshwater. Called ''cooling food'' - beats summer heat. Used medicinally (anti-diabetic, anti-inflammatory). Thrives in monsoon. Farmers grow fish for half year, then water chestnuts. pH 6.7-8.2 ideal. Planted at monsoon beginning. Traditional Ayurvedic use. Made into flour, used fresh. Perfectly adapted to Tropical monsoon wetland agriculture. Can be integrated